Identify Core Entities (Day 3 – Coding Prep)

⏱️ Time: 20–40 mins
🎯 Goal: Decide what objects must exist in our system before writing code

🔹 What Is a Core Entity?

A core entity is something that:

Has a unique identity

Has state (data)

Lives for a long time

Represents a real business concept

If it disappears, your system stops making sense.

🔹 Rules to Identify Entities (Very Important)

Ask these 3 questions:

1️⃣ Does it have a unique ID?
2️⃣ Does it change over time?
3️⃣ Does the business care about it?

If YES to all → Entity ✅

🔹 Our Banking Domain → Core Entities

Let’s do this cleanly and professionally.

1️⃣ User

📌 Represents a bank customer

Why entity?

Has identity (userId)

Exists independently

Owns accounts

Key attributes (conceptual):

userId

name

email

phone

⚠️ Rule:

User does NOT store balance

2️⃣ Account

📌 Where money actually lives

Why entity?

Has accountNumber

Balance changes

Core to banking

Key attributes:

accountId

userId

balance

status (ACTIVE / BLOCKED)

🔥 Critical Rule:

Only Account can modify balance

3️⃣ Transaction

📌 Records money movement

Why entity?

Immutable record

Required for audit

Has lifecycle

Key attributes:

transactionId

fromAccountId

toAccountId

amount

status (INITIATED, SUCCESS, FAILED)

timestamp

⚠️ Rule:

Transactions never update balance directly

4️⃣ Notification

📌 Informational entity

Why entity?

Has delivery state

Stored for retry

Async by nature

Key attributes:

notificationId

userId

message

status (PENDING, SENT, FAILED)

🔹 Entity Relationship (Mental Model)
User
 └── Account (1..N)
        └── Transaction (many)
User
 └── Notification (many)


Key point:

Account is money owner

Transaction is history

Notification is side-effect

🔹 What We Are NOT Making Entities (On Purpose)

❌ BalanceHistory
❌ TransferRequest
❌ PaymentProcessor

These will be:

DTOs

Services

Events

👉 This is how you avoid overengineering.

🔹 Microservices Hint (Don’t Implement Yet)

Later, these entities map naturally to services:

Entity	Future Service
User	User Service
Account	Account Service
Transaction	Transaction Service
Notification	Notification Service

This is clean system design thinking.

🎯 Interview Gold Line

“Entities represent long-lived business objects with identity and state. In banking systems, account owns balance, transaction ensures auditability, and notifications

Nice, this is where good engineers separate themselves from average ones 👍
We’re still not coding yet — we’re deciding who is responsible for what.

🧭 Define Entity Responsibilities (Day 3 – Core Design)

⏱️ Time: 40–60 mins
🎯 Goal: Prevent god-objects and misplaced logic

🔹 What Does “Responsibility” Mean?

Responsibility = what an entity is allowed to do and what it must never do

If responsibilities are unclear:

Business rules leak everywhere

Microservices become messy

Bugs multiply

🔹 Golden Rule

An entity protects its own invariants

(Invariants = rules that must always be true)

1️⃣ User — Responsibilities
✅ Responsible For

Holding user identity & profile

Owning accounts

Receiving notifications

❌ NOT Responsible For

Balance handling

Money transfer

Transaction processing

📌 Why?

User is a person, not a wallet.

2️⃣ Account — Responsibilities (MOST IMPORTANT)
✅ Responsible For

Maintaining balance

Credit money

Debit money

Enforcing balance rules

❌ NOT Responsible For

Logging transactions

Sending notifications

Cross-account transfers

🔥 Invariants:

Balance ≥ 0

Account must be ACTIVE

💡 Interview line:

“Account is the aggregate root for monetary consistency.”

3️⃣ Transaction — Responsibilities
✅ Responsible For

Recording money movement

Tracking transaction status

Ensuring immutability

❌ NOT Responsible For

Updating balance

Retrying transfers

Sending notifications

📌 Rule:

Transactions describe what happened, not what should happen

4️⃣ Notification — Responsibilities
✅ Responsible For

Message content

Delivery status

Retry tracking

❌ NOT Responsible For

Business decisions

Transaction validation

Blocking core flow

🔥 Rule:

Notifications must be event-driven & async

🔹 Responsibility Boundary Visualization
Account
 ├── debit()
 ├── credit()
 └── validateBalance()

Transaction
 └── record()

Notification
 └── sendAsync()


No cross-contamination ❌

🔹 Common Beginner Mistakes (Avoid These)

❌ AccountService updating balance directly
❌ Transaction updating account balance
❌ Notification failure rolling back transaction
❌ User having balance field

These kill scalability.

🔹 How This Helps Microservices

Clear responsibilities ⇒

Account Service owns money

Transaction Service owns audit

Notification Service is async & decoupled

No distributed mess later.

🧪 Self-Check (Critical Thinking)

Answer mentally:

1️⃣ Who validates sufficient balance?
2️⃣ Who records transfer history?
3️⃣ Who retries failed notifications?

If answers are:

Account

Transaction

Notification

👉 You’re on the right track ✅
What Is an Aggregate?

An Aggregate is a cluster of entities that must be consistent together.

One entity is the Aggregate Root

All access goes through the root

Other entities inside cannot be modified directly

🔹 Why Aggregates Matter

Without aggregates:

Multiple services update same data

Distributed transactions everywhere

Race conditions & data corruption

With aggregates:

Strong consistency inside

Loose coupling outside

Safe microservices split

🔹 Banking System Aggregates (Key Decision)

Let’s define exact boundaries.

1️⃣ Account Aggregate (MOST CRITICAL)
🟢 Aggregate Root: Account
🧩 Inside Aggregate

Account

Balance (value)

AccountStatus

❌ Outside Aggregate

Transaction

User

Notification

📌 Why?

Balance consistency must be local and atomic

Rules:

Only Account can change balance

Debit + validation happens in one transaction

Account Aggregate
 ├── accountId
 ├── balance
 ├── debit()
 └── credit()


🔥 This is non-negotiable in banking systems.

2️⃣ Transaction Aggregate
🟢 Aggregate Root: Transaction
🧩 Inside Aggregate

Transaction

TransactionStatus

Timestamp

❌ Outside Aggregate

Account balance

Notifications

📌 Why?

Transactions are historical records, not consistency holders

Transaction Aggregate
 ├── transactionId
 ├── fromAccountId
 ├── toAccountId
 └── status


Immutable after SUCCESS/FAILED.

3️⃣ User Aggregate
🟢 Aggregate Root: User
🧩 Inside Aggregate

User

Profile info

❌ Outside Aggregate

Account balance

Transactions

📌 Why?

User data changes independently of money

4️⃣ Notification Aggregate
🟢 Aggregate Root: Notification
🧩 Inside Aggregate

Message

Delivery status

Retry count

📌 Rule:

Failures must NOT affect money flow

🔹 Aggregate Communication Rule (Very Important)

Aggregates do NOT update each other directly

They communicate via:

IDs

Events

Service orchestration

❌ No cross-aggregate DB joins
❌ No shared transactions

🔹 Example: Money Transfer (Conceptual)
1. TransactionService creates Transaction (INITIATED)
2. AccountService debits Account A
3. AccountService credits Account B
4. Transaction marked SUCCESS
5. Notification event published


Each aggregate updates independently, safely.

🔹 Interview Power Statement

“Aggregates define transactional boundaries. In banking systems, Account is the aggregate root for balance consistency, while Transaction remains an immutable audit record.”

Say this and interviewers nod 😄

🧪 Self-Check (Important)

Answer mentally:

1️⃣ Can Transaction update Account balance? → ❌
2️⃣ Can Notification failure rollback debit? → ❌
3️⃣ Can Account change balance without validation? → ❌

If all ❌ → correct design
Service Layer vs Domain Layer (Day 3 – Architecture Core)

⏱️ Time: 90–120 mins
🎯 Goal: Decide where business logic lives and where orchestration lives

🔹 Big Picture (One Line)

Domain Layer = business rules
Service Layer = use-case orchestration

Never mix them.

🔹 Layered View (Mental Model)
Controller
   ↓
Application / Service Layer
   ↓
Domain Layer
   ↓
Repository


Controllers talk to services, not domain objects directly.

🔹 Domain Layer (THE HEART ❤️)
What Lives Here?

✅ Entities
✅ Value Objects
✅ Business rules
✅ Invariants

What NEVER Lives Here?

❌ HTTP
❌ Kafka
❌ Databases
❌ Spring annotations

📌 Domain layer must be pure Java.

Example: Account Domain Logic (Conceptual)
Account.debit(amount)


Rules enforced here:

balance >= amount

account is ACTIVE

👉 Domain decides if something is allowed.

🔹 Service Layer (THE BRAIN 🧠)
What Lives Here?

✅ Use-case flows
✅ Coordination between aggregates
✅ Transactions (@Transactional)
✅ Calling repositories
✅ Publishing events

What NEVER Lives Here?

❌ Core business rules
❌ Balance calculations

📌 Service layer decides when and in what order things happen.

Example: TransferMoney Service Flow
1. Load Account A
2. Load Account B
3. Account A → debit
4. Account B → credit
5. Save accounts
6. Create transaction record
7. Publish notification event


Service orchestrates, domain validates.

🔹 Bad Design (Common Mistake ❌)
if(account.getBalance() >= amount) {
   account.setBalance(account.getBalance() - amount);
}


Why bad?

Rule outside domain

Duplicate logic risk

Hard to test

🔹 Good Design (Correct ✅)
account.debit(amount);


Domain enforces rules

Service just calls

Clean and testable

🔹 Responsibility Comparison Table
Layer	Responsibility
Domain	What is allowed
Service	When & how
Controller	Request/response
Repository	Persistence
🔹 How This Helps Microservices

Clean separation ⇒

Easier service extraction

Less coupling

Clear ownership

Account Service contains:

Account domain

Account service

Account repository

🔹 Interview Killer Line

“The domain layer encapsulates business rules and invariants, while the service layer orchestrates use cases and coordinates between aggregates.”

💯

